metadata.name: Parhun پَرهون #114
metadata.description:
Parhun is our first generative piece. It uses handcrafted tiles paired 
with generative programming. Inspired by the Middle East's unique shapes and patterns 
like stars on the Persian kilims and the shape of the monument Domes combined with 
geometric shapes. It reflects the unique and complex nature of our home.

Every buyer gets 5 out of more than 30 carefully curated color palettes and an 
exhaustive amount of tile combinations bound to some unique property combinations.

Every piece is a generated SVG and can be printed in any size.

Click / Space Key -> New grid / palette

Ctrl / Cmd + P -> Print

metadata.name: Drei #378
metadata.description:
For Lia Drei (https://www.archivioguerrieridrei.com/biografia-1?lang=en)

This morning I thought about all the work I did with triangles... the idea came to me that the right triangle is the symbol of creation...(…)
The hypotenuse is the love that unites and gives life. The tip of the triangle is the uterus which makes the space grow.
-- LIA DREI (Diaries, 2004)

My paintings have no past, they are empty of meaning in the present, but await the discussions of the future, as remotely as possible.
And this is why they don't have their feet firmly planted in the ground, although there are invisible roots that take life from the earth, like so many blades of grass.
While I work I look for the truth in what I do. The time is not yesterday because it would be false, it is not today because the emotion takes my breath away and I die every moment and am reborn after every new brushstroke.
Soon after, time becomes old, useless, meaningless. I never know what will come out with the next brushstroke or spatula stroke.
My thoughts go at supersonic speed and only stop to choose another color. The one just painted is never the right one. So I live the life of the new painting with the sense of mystery that the moonless night has. (…)
-- LIA DREI (Notes, 1962)

----

I never talk about myself.

I'm not creative.
I blatantly steal other people's art.
I'm a bad coder, I copy, paste, mix ideas.
I often ruin it, degrade it.
But I always make it mine what I like.

I absorb.

-- ALESSANDRO FIORE (fxhash, 2024)


—————

The work is created responsive by default and it will adapt to the browser window. It will change (even consistently in some cases) based on the screen aspect ratio.

Key commands:

1 = Square 2000x2000
2 = Square 4000x4000
3 = Square 6000x6000 (Dependent on your browser limitations, tested on Safari (Mac))
p = Portrait 1500x2115
l = Landscape 2115x1500
e = Responsive/Default
f = Fullscreen
s = Save as image

metadata.name: Precision: micro #166
metadata.description: Precision: micro is the next entry in my "Precisions" series. It focuses on smaller shapes in smaller spaces, where individual elements are placed, overwritten, removed, and sectioned out.  My previous Precisions pieces used exact placements to reach a sense of balance, but with micro, I've introduced removal as an instrument of balance.

metadata.name: Geometric Motion #44
metadata.description:
Inspired by minimalist graphic designs, this work is an exploration of combinations for simple geometrical shapes. The shapes slide under others, go out of view and reappear in an ever-changing canvas.

On a grid of 4 to 7 cells we place triangles, squares, and circles of different sizes. Their color and draw order are determined by their initial row placement. They move around freely inside the canvas indefinitely, showing a quasi-infinite number of combinations.

There are 10 possible colors, with 2 that are very rare that change the blend method to "exclusion" or "difference".

Coded with p5js

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2021

metadata.name: Entangled Miasma #57
metadata.description:
Time is the only reason we do not perceive the violence of plants, and scale the reason we do not see the violence of microbes. They grow, grab, breakdown, decimate, and devour all around us.
Speed, density, limbs, curl, color and more define differences across them. Each is thriving and waiting for you.
Made with P5.js
10% of profits go to the Processing Foundation

metadata.name: {Lumina} #3
metadata.description:
The restitution of a breath
Your breath is your artwork

{Lumina} is part of the installation Σ Lumina taking place at Musée d’Orsay. A free live minting is scheduled from February 13th to March 10th, 2024. 

Breath, the vital essence, embodies our interconnection. It carries our shared heritage. A medium that helps Σ Lumina to unite the physical and the digital, the living with the coded. The voices of Orsay resonate within us, their breath becoming ours, landscaping our common creation.


Art curators of {Le Code d’Orsay}:
Christophe Leribault,
Président de l’Établissement public du musée d’Orsay et du musée de l’Orangerie
Virginie Donzeaud, Administratrice générale adjointe

16x16
HTML, js, Webgl
Location: Musée d’Orsay
